Wild Theory #2: Indigenous Cannibal tribe
According to Boquete locals, the girls were eaten by an indigenous cannibal tribe that lived in the jungle. The cannibal natives are known as the Rabbit Indians or Indios Conejo. Sounds farfetched, right? But what if it’s true? 
Several reddit users have heard the same story from people in Panama. And if we look at the evidence, it's somewhat possible. The fact that Lisanne's backpack was found in very good condition could indicate that someone had taken them and kept them somewhere before leaving the girls’ belongings along the banks of a river. Authorities also found 30 different fingerprints on the backpack which were unaccounted for. 
Moreover, inside the backpack, the authorities found Lisanne's camera, both of the girls' phones, and some cash. Not only were these items not stolen, but they were also in near-perfect condition. How would this be possible if someone had not kept these items secured somewhere safe? And why would the murderers not be interested in the camera, cash, and two phones? It would be in their best interest to ensure these items never see the light of day. But for natives who live in the jungle, material things like these may not be useful enough to keep.
That’s not all. The night photos in the camera may not have been made by the girls. Some theorize that the photos seemed to have been taken by someone who didn’t know how to use a camera. Maybe someone who was playing around with it. If the girls were taken by cannibal natives, it’s possible that one or more persons in the tribe was curious about their stuff and played around with the camera. This can also explain why there were so many fingerprints on the backpack.
The remains found could also be used to support this theory. First, there weren't any teeth scratches or other indicative markings that point towards the remains being eaten by animals. If the bones were dragged by the natural current of the river, then scratches would also be present. But there were none. Second, none of the big bones were found, including the skulls. According to experts, there are no animals in that wilderness that would eat a skull. So, where are they? 
Third, Kris' bones were "bleached." According to some experts, this type of bleaching is not natural or accidental. The type of bleaching on the bones could only be intentional. Decomposition of the bodies would take a minimum of 3 weeks to occur under normal conditions. However, the cooler elevation and rainfall in the area would have prolonged this process. In addition, bleaching requires the bones to be exposed to ample direct sunlight. However, based on rainfall data of the area, there weren't many sunny days during that time. Moreover, sunlight does not bleach bones evenly. There should be gradients of discoloration or “shadows” on the bone. With Kris’ pelvic bones, the bleaching is uniform.
And then there’s the presence of phosphorus on her bones. An analysis made by The Chiriquí Institute of Legal Medicine and Forensic Sciences (IMELCF) suggests that lime was probably used in the deconstruction of her body. But there were no traces of phosphates in the soil samples collected from the area. This discovery implies that the presence of this chemical on Kris’ bones was not natural. In fact, we can confidently assume that someone or multiple someones used chemicals to bleach her bones.  
Another interesting point is that Kris' pelvic bones were broken in two places. Bones don't generally break easily even if they were washed away by a strong current. The pelvic bone, in particular, is typically strong and don’t break easily, especially in young people. So, what could have caused them to break? We don’t know. But it’s probably not a natural cause.
And it’s not just Kris’ and Lisanne’s bones that were found. The forensic investigators also found bones of three other people. According an IMELCF spokesperson, these bones were likely from a “washed-out indigenous cemetery.” But it boggles the mind that a native tribe who is very familiar with the flooding that occurs at the river every year would build a cemetery near it. 
Moreover, Kris' bones had no flesh attached while Lisanne's still had some. This meant that there are inconsistencies between the rate of decay of the girls' bodies. More importantly, it takes more than 2 months for bodies to have decomposed into skeletons. So, why was one a skeleton and the other still had flesh on it? Could it be that Kris was eaten first and Lisanne was killed later?
Of course, every piece of evidence we used to support this theory can also be used to serve as proof that the two girls were murdered BUT not eaten. There’s really no evidence that such a tribe exists in that area. Then again, maybe it’s because no one who has ever encountered them have survived.
